    "Maximum temperature was found most sensitive in yield prediction FIGURE 4 | Bar plot of estimated effects of six weather components on corn measured for 52 weeks of each year, starting from January.",
    "The vertical axes were normalized across all weather components to make the effects comparable.",
    "around week 20, a period that typically coincides with corn planting (May 13).",
    "From an agronomic perspective, temperature is very important at that period because it affects seed germination and emergence, and typically high temperature results in fast and uniform emergence while low temperatures in slow and non-uniform emergence that affect plant growth yield.",
    "The minimum temperature was most sensitive around weeks 22 (May 30) and 35 (August 26)."
